of ordering the covert effort

19:28.533 --> 19:30.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to help Trump get elected.

19:30.066 --> 19:32.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Nick Schifrin in Washington.

19:32.766 --> 19:37.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Late today, the
Senate Judiciary Committee said
that Donald Trump Jr. and former

19:39.733 --> 19:43.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump campaign manager Paul
Manafort will testify next
Wednesday about their meeting

19:44.533 --> 19:46.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with a Russian
lawyer last summer.

19:46.633 --> 19:51.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president's son-in-law,
Jared Kushner, goes before the
Senate Intelligence Committee

19:51.100 --> 19:55.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on Monday.

19:55.733 --> 20:00.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

20:04.966 --> 20:09.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the
"NewsHour": what proposed
cuts to food stamps could
mean for Trump voters;

20:11.833 --> 20:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how Tesla's new cheaper
electric car could shape the
industry's future; and "Devil's

20:17.533 --> 20:22.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bargain," a new book about White
House strategist Steve Bannon.

20:22.500 --> 20:27.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: President
Trump continues to repeat
the unsubstantiated
claim that millions of

20:28.666 --> 20:31.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
illegal votes were cast
in the 2016 election.

20:31.733 --> 20:36.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The commission he set
up to look into this has
sparked its own controversy.

20:36.233 --> 20:38.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham reports.

20:38.333 --> 20:40.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of
the United States: Every time
voter fraud occurs, it cancels

20:40.500 --> 20:44.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
out the vote of a lawful citizen
and undermines democracy.

20:44.566 --> 20:48.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The first
meeting of the Commission on
Election Integrity convened

20:48.866 --> 20:50.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with a presidential
defense of its mission.

20:50.933 --> 20:55.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Throughout the
campaign, and even after,
people would come up to me and

20:58.200 --> 21:01.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
express their concerns
about voter inconsistencies
and irregularities
which they saw, in some

21:04.566 --> 21:08.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cases having to do with
very large numbers of
people in certain states.

21:08.466 --> 21:13.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So far, those
allegations remain unproven,
but the commission is pressing

21:13.166 --> 21:15.300 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ahead.

21:15.300 --> 21:19.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last month, it sent letters to
every state, asking for voter
information, including names,

21:20.500 --> 21:23.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
birthdays and partial
Social Security numbers.

21:23.066 --> 21:27.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Seventeen states, governed
by Republicans and Democrats,
as well as the District of

21:27.400 --> 21:29.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Columbia, refused to comply.

21:29.966 --> 21:34.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many others said they
will provide only limited
information that's already
publicly available.

21:34.400 --> 21:38.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, the president
criticized those states
who've refused to go along.

21:38.366 --> 21:42.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: One has to wonder
what they're worried about.

21:42.800 --> 21:47.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I ask the vice president
and I ask the commission,
what are they worried about?

21:47.733 --> 21:49.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's something.

21:49.200 --> 21:51.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
There always is.

21:51.333 --> 21:54.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Just after
the election, when Hillary
Clinton won the popular vote

21:54.800 --> 21:59.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by 2.8 million votes, Mr. Trump
tweeted, again, with no evidence
whatsoever, that the vote

22:01.900 --> 22:05.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
count was skewed -- quote --
"I won the popular vote if you
deduct the millions of people

22:06.366 --> 22:08.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
who voted illegally."

22:08.366 --> 22:12.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The commission co-chair,
Kansas Secretary of State Kris
Kobach, who is a Republican,

22:12.100 --> 22:15.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says the country deserves
a hard, dispassionate
look at the issue.

22:15.533 --> 22:17.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KRIS KOBACH (R), Kansas
Secretary of State: For a long
time, there has been lingering

22:17.500 --> 22:21.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doubt among many Americans
about integrity and
fairness of elections.

22:21.333 --> 22:23.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it's not a new issue at all.

22:23.866 --> 22:26.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If you look at polling
data, it goes back decades.

22:26.533 --> 22:30.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The panel is
chaired by Vice President Pence,
and in addition to Kobach,

22:30.900 --> 22:35.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
members include current and
former secretaries of state from
Indiana, New Hampshire, Maine

22:36.633 --> 22:38.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and Ohio, among others.

22:38.633 --> 22:43.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But critics of the commission
warn that stoking fears of
alleged fraud will be used later

22:44.600 --> 22:46.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to justify a crackdown
on voting rights.

22:46.633 --> 22:50.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rick Hasen is a law professor
at the University of California,
Irvine, and an election law

22:50.900 --> 22:53.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
expert.

22:53.033 --> 22:55.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RICK HASEN, University
of California, Irvine:
I'm concerned that it's
going to be something

22:55.666 --> 22:57.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that is just going to try
to support the president's
agenda, claiming that
there's a lot of voter

22:57.833 --> 23:01.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fraud, and use that to make
it harder for people to be
able to register to vote.

23:01.633 --> 23:05.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Already, the
commission is facing at least
seven lawsuits questioning

23:05.966 --> 23:10.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
its transparency, conduct
and even its existence.

23:10.733 --> 23:14.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We turn now to two
officials who actually run
elections in their states.

23:14.800 --> 23:17.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Matthew Dunlap is the
secretary of state for Maine.

23:17.033 --> 23:20.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He is a Democrat, and
he's also a member of the
president's commission.

23:20.433 --> 23:22.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And he was at today's meeting.

23:22.200 --> 23:23.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We're also joined
by Michele Reagan.

23:23.933 --> 23:27.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She is a Republican and she is
Arizona's secretary of state.

23:27.366 --> 23:29.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

23:29.366 --> 23:31.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW DUNLAP (D),
Maine Secretary of State:
Thank you for having us.

23:31.300 --> 23:32.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHELE REAGAN (R),
Arizona Secretary of State:
Thank you for having us.

23:32.900 --> 23:34.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM:
Matthew, I would love
to start with you first.

23:34.966 --> 23:36.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is your general hope that
this commission - - what do
you hope it will accomplish?

23:36.933 --> 23:40.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW DUNLAP: Well, my general
hope is that actually we do
something to bolster voter

23:40.233 --> 23:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
confidence in how we conduct
elections in this country.

23:42.500 --> 23:44.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think we have an awful
lot to be proud of.

23:44.633 --> 23:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No one is questioning the
legitimacy of the outcome
of the 2016 election.

23:48.100 --> 23:52.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There are some lingering
questions about how
elections have been
conducted, who was able

23:52.666 --> 23:54.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to vote legally or not.

23:54.633 --> 23:58.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, and based on my
experience in the state of
Maine, I think we can very, very

23:58.833 --> 24:02.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
proud of what our local election
officials have done to make
sure that their neighbors

24:02.800 --> 24:06.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
get to exercise their democratic
right of self-governance.

24:06.200 --> 24:10.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Michele
Reagan, I know you are
a supporter broadly
of this commission

24:10.966 --> 24:13.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and its aims.

24:13.033 --> 24:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As you know, the commission
was set up in part because of
the president's concern that

24:16.033 --> 24:20.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there had been some voter
fraud in the past election.

24:20.233 --> 24:21.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm curious.

24:21.666 --> 24:24.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You were running the election
in Arizona back in 2016.

24:24.733 --> 24:27.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Did you have any instances
of fraud in your state?

24:27.733 --> 24:31.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHELE REAGAN: Well, I can't
speak, obviously, for other
states, but I know, in Arizona,

24:31.733 --> 24:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have a number of measures
that we use to prevent fraud.

24:35.733 --> 24:38.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that's not to say
fraud never happens.

24:38.100 --> 24:42.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Certainly, when we hear
allegations of that, we
take it very seriously.

24:42.800 --> 24:47.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But it's important to
note Arizona has some
laws on the books that
keep it very safe from

24:48.533 --> 24:50.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
fraud, massive fraud.

24:50.566 --> 24:54.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One is the showing proof of
I.D. at the polling places.

24:54.766 --> 24:58.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Another is proof of citizenship
when registering to vote.

24:58.333 --> 25:00.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
A lot of states don't
have these laws.

25:00.500 --> 25:05.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, speaking from Arizona's
point of view, coupled with the
fact that we also participate,

25:07.366 --> 25:11.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
already, in interstate
cross-check systems,
for instances, of
double voting or double

25:13.300 --> 25:16.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
registration, we're pretty
confident in Arizona that we
run a really good election.

25:16.933 --> 25:21.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Matthew
Dunlap, as I mentioned
in the report prior to
this, the commission

25:23.366 --> 25:25.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
asked all the states for some
types of voter information.

25:25.733 --> 25:27.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And there was a lot of concern.

25:27.266 --> 25:28.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Many states pushed back.

25:28.733 --> 25:31.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I understand Maine didn't
share its information.

25:31.000 --> 25:33.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Explain to me, what
is the concern?

25:33.000 --> 25:34.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What are you worried about?

25:34.500 --> 25:35.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MATTHEW DUNLAP: Well, we're not
really worried about anything.

25:35.766 --> 25:37.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We just follow the law.

25:37.766 --> 25:41.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The request that came from the
commission, which, as commission
members, we did not review

25:41.000 --> 25:43.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the full text of the
letter that went out.

25:43.533 --> 25:48.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We did agree that the
information that should
be requested should be
requested, not demanded,

25:50.933 --> 25:52.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and it should only be that
information that would
be publicly available
to anyone legally

25:52.466 --> 25:55.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
entitled to obtain it under
those particular state laws.

25:55.133 --> 26:00.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When we got the request, the
letter said that be advised that
any information that you provide

26:01.500 --> 26:04.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will be made publicly available
for anyone to inspect.

26:04.533 --> 26:09.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Maine election law specifies
that anyone who is qualified
to access the voter file must

26:09.400 --> 26:11.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
keep it confidential.

26:11.166 --> 26:13.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that is directory language.

26:13.466 --> 26:16.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Making the list available is
discretionary under the law.

26:16.600 --> 26:20.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, with that direction, it was
a mathematical equation for us.

26:20.100 --> 26:22.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We simply could not provide
it under those circumstances.

26:22.233 --> 26:24.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And so we didn't.

26:24.733 --> 26:26.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Michele
Reagan, do you have
concerns about this
database being compiled

26:26.733 --> 26:28.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
here in Washington, D.C.?

26:28.166 --> 26:30.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHELE REAGAN: Well,
absolutely we have concerns.

26:30.233 --> 26:34.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, again, in Arizona, we
just looked to the statutes
and the law to tell us exactly

26:34.733 --> 26:37.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
what we were going to
have to do or not do.

26:37.866 --> 26:42.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the law is pretty clear
that, again, just like in Maine,
you can't take the information

26:45.366 --> 26:49.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
via a public records
request with the intent of
sharing it or posting it
publicly or disseminate,

26:50.600 --> 26:53.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you know, giving it out.

26:53.100 --> 26:56.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Matthew
Dunlap, what about this larger
concern that has been raised by

26:56.766 --> 27:01.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some people that this commission
and its mission is going to be
used to justify further national

27:04.133 --> 27:05.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
crackdown on voting rights?

27:05.566 --> 27:07.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you make of that?

27:07.633 --> 27:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW DUNLAP: That's one of
my favorite questions to get
out of all of this, is that

27:09.433 --> 27:14.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
somehow we're trying to
undo the electoral process.

27:14.133 --> 27:17.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My position is, is that you have
these lingering questions that
have been around for a while

27:17.866 --> 27:20.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
now about illegal
activity around elections.

27:20.766 --> 27:23.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Sunshine is the
greatest disinfectant.

27:23.266 --> 27:28.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have full confidence
that everything that's
been claimed will probably
be largely debunked.

27:30.000 --> 27:33.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And what we will find
will probably be the
product of mistakes and
errors and unintended

27:34.433 --> 27:36.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
actions that were never
meant to become felonies.

27:36.733 --> 27:40.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think, you know, with that
understanding, I think we're
going to find that we have a

27:40.933 --> 27:45.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really pretty good system
that's very, very decentralized,
which actually adds to its

27:45.033 --> 27:48.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
level of security against some
of the allegations that we have
heard about, like the Russian

27:48.733 --> 27:51.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Federation getting involved
in hacking our elections.

27:51.800 --> 27:55.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the systems that we
have in place, which are run
by local election officials,

27:55.766 --> 27:59.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually will be found to
work very, very well, and that
American voters should feel

27:59.600 --> 28:03.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pretty good about the systems
that help us elect our
leadership and decide issues.

28:03.866 --> 28:08.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM:
Michele Reagan, you heard
Matthew here say that he
believes the commission

28:08.733 --> 28:10.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
will largely debunk
many of these claims.

28:10.833 --> 28:15.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But just today, the co-chairman
of the commission, Kris Kobach,
said on MSNBC that he says, we

28:17.800 --> 28:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
may never know whether
or not Hillary Clinton in
fact won the popular vote.

28:22.266 --> 28:27.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is an implication that is
very likely the potential that
three million illegal votes

28:27.866 --> 28:29.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
were cast.

28:29.933 --> 28:34.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is the head of the commission
is making that kind of a
statement, does that concern you

28:34.033 --> 28:37.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
at all about the thrust
of this commission?

28:37.033 --> 28:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHELE REAGAN: What really
concerns me is the good work
that the commission could be

28:42.500 --> 28:45.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
doing.

28:45.000 --> 28:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I hope -- and I have
high hopes that they
will look forward to
some of these suggestions

28:48.833 --> 28:51.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that states are making.

28:51.333 --> 28:55.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would hope that this
commission takes what
states are doing and
determines what is working

28:57.066 --> 28:59.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
best, so they can share
it with other states.

28:59.033 --> 29:01.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Michele Reagan, Matthew Dunlap,
thank you both very much.

29:01.700 --> 29:06.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MATTHEW DUNLAP: Thank
you for having us.

29:06.500 --> 29:11.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Congressional
Republicans yesterday unveiled
a budget that would dramatically

29:18.166 --> 29:23.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
curb spending on a
host of social welfare
programs, including the
federal government's

29:25.133 --> 29:28.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Supplemental Nutrition
Assistance Program, or SNAP,
better known as food stamps.

29:30.433 --> 29:33.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president's budget released
earlier this year also included
deep cuts to the program.

29:33.666 --> 29:38.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To see how those proposals
might play out, "NewsHour"
special correspondent Cat Wise

29:40.500 --> 29:43.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
recently traveled to
Arkansas, a state that voted
heavily for Mr. Trump.

29:43.966 --> 29:48.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This report is part of Chasing
the Dream, our ongoing series
on poverty and opportunity

29:49.566 --> 29:52.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in America.

29:52.033 --> 29:55.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: In the small
town of Thornton, Arkansas,
Joannie Cayce fires up
her truck twice a month,

29:59.700 --> 30:04.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and drives to a Wal-Mart about
30 miles away to stock up on
fruits, vegetables, meat, milk

30:06.033 --> 30:09.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and other products
donated by the company.

30:09.200 --> 30:14.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When she returns to the local
food pantry her family has
run since the 1950s, some 200

30:17.300 --> 30:20.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
residents are waiting, and
a desperate rush begins.

30:20.500 --> 30:25.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: We get paid every two
weeks, and, by the end of the
week, it's like the cupboards

30:26.866 --> 30:28.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are bare, and we're
ramen noodling, you know?

30:28.900 --> 30:32.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: I got two kids at
the house and stuff that's
hungry that I have to feed.

30:32.533 --> 30:37.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Ms. Cayce, as she's
known here, says the number
of people she serves each

30:37.033 --> 30:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
month has nearly doubled in
the past year-and-a-half,
from 350 to 650, even
as the state's economy

30:44.733 --> 30:46.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has improved.

30:46.766 --> 30:50.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOANNIE CAYCE, Cayce Charities:
We see no employment, no
grocery stores, no craft stores.

30:52.300 --> 30:55.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Mostly, the families
are generationally poor,
and they can't move.

30:55.000 --> 30:57.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't have the money to
move or anywhere to go to move.

30:57.600 --> 31:02.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: The day we
visited, Brittney Williams
came to Ms. Cayce's with
her two young daughters.

31:04.666 --> 31:08.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At mid-month, she's already
run out of the $231 a month
she receives in food stamps,

31:11.200 --> 31:15.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or SNAP, the federal
government's Supplemental
Nutrition Assistance
Program for the poor.

31:17.233 --> 31:20.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRITTNEY WILLIAMS, Receives
SNAP Assistance: I'm out of
food stamps within two weeks.

31:20.600 --> 31:25.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's another two weeks
week-and-a-half, two weeks,
that I'm sitting here, well, how

31:26.700 --> 31:28.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
am I going to feed my kids?

31:28.233 --> 31:30.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You know, what am
I going to do next?

31:30.633 --> 31:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Am I going to have to beg people
for food, or go to Ms. Cayce,
or what if Ms. Cayce don't

31:37.100 --> 31:40.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
come back to me in
time, and I run out?

31:40.300 --> 31:44.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Brittney's husband,
Daryl, works full-time as a
security guard at the local

31:44.900 --> 31:47.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sawmill, making $11 an hour.

31:47.433 --> 31:51.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says the family's bills
have been piling up for months,
and that they're now facing

31:51.300 --> 31:53.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
eviction.

31:53.333 --> 31:54.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DARYL WILLIAMS, Receives
SNAP Assistance: I have got
a truck payment outside.

31:54.633 --> 31:57.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I have got all the
utilities in here.

31:57.100 --> 32:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After buying pull-ups and wipes
for them included, I have got
maybe $50 to $100 left a month,

32:04.066 --> 32:06.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that's got to go in for
gas, so I can get back and
forth to work for the next two

32:06.400 --> 32:08.533 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
weeks.

32:08.533 --> 32:12.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CAT WISE: To qualify for
food stamps, a family
of four in Arkansas must
make less than $32,000

32:12.333 --> 32:14.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a year.

32:14.366 --> 32:18.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last year, 14 percent of the
state's population was on
SNAP, or about 426,000 people.

32:20.133 --> 32:22.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That percentage mirrors
the national picture.

32:22.966 --> 32:27.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2016, 44 million
Americans were on SNAP,
receiving an average
benefit of $126 per person

32:30.800 --> 32:33.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
per month, or
about $1.40 a meal.

32:33.433 --> 32:37.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For years, the program has
been in the crosshairs of
conservative lawmakers,
who say the government

32:39.700 --> 32:43.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
simply can't sustain a federal
program that last year cost $71
billion, up from $33 billion

32:46.333 --> 32:48.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in 2007, before the recession.

32:48.166 --> 32:50.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

32:50.233 --> 32:51.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRUCE WESTERMAN (R), Arkansas:
Instead of lifting people
out of poverty, many of our

32:51.766 --> 32:54.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
welfare programs are actually
trapping people in poverty.

32:54.466 --> 32:59.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Bruce Westerman is the
Republican U.S. representative
of the 4th District in

32:59.433 --> 33:01.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Arkansas, which
includes Thornton.

33:01.000 --> 33:03.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

33:03.066 --> 33:05.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRUCE WESTERMAN: We have
got to do something to get
the debt under control.

33:05.400 --> 33:10.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's either do it the easy way
now, which may not seem easy
to some, or have the whole

33:12.466 --> 33:15.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thing come crashing down and
not be able to provide SNAP,
or Medicare and Medicaid or

33:15.500 --> 33:18.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
anything to anyone because
we're in a financial crisis.

33:18.500 --> 33:23.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: Mick Mulvaney is
the Trump administration's
director of the Office
of Management and Budget.

33:25.400 --> 33:27.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICK MULVANEY, White House
Budget Director: We're no longer
going to measure compassion

33:27.466 --> 33:31.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by the number of programs or
the number of people on those
programs, but by the number

33:31.233 --> 33:33.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of people we help get
off of those programs.

33:33.766 --> 33:37.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: In May, the
White House presented its
budget, which aimed to
slash federal spending

33:37.533 --> 33:41.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
by $3.6 trillion
over the next decade.

33:41.400 --> 33:46.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If Congress were to pass that
budget, SNAP would lose $193
billion, around a quarter

33:47.600 --> 33:49.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of its funding.

33:49.666 --> 33:54.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The plan calls for tightening
standards on who qualifies
for the program, and, for the

33:56.200 --> 33:59.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first time, the budget shifts
a large chunk of the cost to
states, starting with 10 percent

34:00.466 --> 34:05.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in 2020 and rising to
25 percent in 2023.

34:05.300 --> 34:10.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For Arkansas, that would
mean $144 million added to
its state budget each year.

34:12.566 --> 34:13.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATHY WEBB (D), Former
Arkansas State Representative:
I don't see where we
would make up that $144

34:13.866 --> 34:15.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
million.

34:15.366 --> 34:17.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CAT WISE: You don't think
the state can make that up?

34:17.800 --> 34:19.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KATHY WEBB: I don't think
the state can make that up.

34:19.933 --> 34:24.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Kathy Webb is a former
state Democratic representative
who now runs the Arkansas Hunger

34:26.800 --> 34:29.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Relief Alliance, a nonprofit
organization connecting and
advocating for the state's

34:29.700 --> 34:31.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
food banks.

34:31.200 --> 34:33.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She says private charities
could not fill the gap.

34:33.233 --> 34:37.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
KATHY WEBB: We cannot
make up the difference.

34:37.166 --> 34:42.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all of the charitable food
network put together is about
a 20th of what the federal

34:43.100 --> 34:45.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
safety net is.

34:45.100 --> 34:49.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Webb also worries
about the effect a SNAP cut
would have on grocery stores in

34:50.000 --> 34:51.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
poor communities.

34:51.500 --> 34:52.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RANDY LINDSEY, Business Owner:
It takes everything to make it.

34:52.300 --> 34:54.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There is no slack.

34:54.333 --> 34:58.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Randy Lindsey and his
wife, Janice, run the Bottom
Dollar Store in Bearden, near

34:58.833 --> 35:01.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thornton.

35:01.033 --> 35:03.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's one of the few stores in
the area selling fresh produce
and meat, as well as household

35:03.533 --> 35:05.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
items, flowers and more.

35:05.566 --> 35:09.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lindsey, a Trump supporter,
says, in a tough economy,
every little bit helps.

35:09.966 --> 35:14.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RANDY LINDSEY: If I
lost 25 percent of SNAP,
for me, it would mean
cutting 10 to 15 hours

35:16.400 --> 35:19.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a week, or roughly 40
hours a month off payroll.

35:19.733 --> 35:21.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CAT WISE: So your employees
would be impacted?

35:21.933 --> 35:22.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RANDY LINDSEY: Yes.

35:22.933 --> 35:24.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It would impact employees.

35:24.133 --> 35:25.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That's a pretty
good chunk to lose.

35:25.866 --> 35:28.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There's not much gravy
in this operation.

35:28.800 --> 35:32.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We make less money, then
something has to be cut.

35:32.066 --> 35:36.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Conservatives often
point out that SNAP expanded
considerably under Presidents

35:36.533 --> 35:40.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
George W. Bush and Barack
Obama, and they are correct.

35:40.300 --> 35:45.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The rise was particularly
acute during the recession of
2008, when millions lost work

35:45.200 --> 35:47.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and joined SNAP's rolls.

35:47.433 --> 35:52.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Benefits were also increased as
part of the Stimulus Act, the
2009 law that pumped billions

35:52.100 --> 35:55.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in federal spending into
communities across the country.

35:55.300 --> 36:00.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yet, since late 2012, both
spending and the number of
people on SNAP have fallen, and

36:02.366 --> 36:06.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the nonpartisan Congressional
Budget Office estimates that,
if no changes were made, the

36:06.300 --> 36:11.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
share of the population
on SNAP would return to
pre-recession levels by 2027.

36:13.166 --> 36:16.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Still, SNAP remains historically
high, as more working families
like the Williams, and

36:18.900 --> 36:23.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seniors like 63-year-old
James Jackson earn less, thus
qualifying for the benefit.

36:25.666 --> 36:28.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES JACKSON, Receives
SNAP Assistance: Anybody,
anyone, at any time can
be affected by poverty.

36:30.833 --> 36:34.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Nearly 25 percent
of all seniors in Arkansas
face the threat of hunger.

36:35.733 --> 36:38.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That leads the nation,
according to a recent report.

36:38.633 --> 36:43.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jackson, a trained chef and
a professional painter, has
struggled to find work since

36:44.366 --> 36:46.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
his truck broke down.

36:46.866 --> 36:51.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He now lives in subsidized
housing in Little Rock
and receives $172 a
month in food stamps.

36:52.633 --> 36:56.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He voted for President
Trump, but urges him
not to make these cuts.

36:56.666 --> 37:01.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES JACKSON: Give me a chance
to get off the very program
that you're trying to cut.

37:03.100 --> 37:05.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I want to get off.

37:05.066 --> 37:10.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But if you take away my ability
to get off, what can I do?

37:12.633 --> 37:17.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: In the long
run, it's more economic
opportunities, rather than
government assistance,

37:19.566 --> 37:21.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that Congressman Westerman
says will best help the
people of his state.

37:21.966 --> 37:24.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

37:24.066 --> 37:26.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRUCE WESTERMAN: It's a shame
that we have to have a program
that large in this country.

37:26.600 --> 37:31.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We need to provide more
opportunities for people that
are good-paying jobs, and not

37:31.466 --> 37:34.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
just jobs, but careers
where they can build
homes and communities.

37:34.600 --> 37:39.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: Back in
Thornton, after the rush
has passed, Joannie Cayce
listens to the desperate

37:40.966 --> 37:43.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
plea of a woman who
couldn't get there today.

37:43.166 --> 37:45.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WOMAN: I am a
grandmother of four.

37:45.700 --> 37:46.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I live alone.

37:46.733 --> 37:48.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Please, please, help me.

37:48.833 --> 37:53.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOANNIE CAYCE: It's the people
that don't come in, it's the
people that live 30 miles

37:57.233 --> 38:02.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
outside of this little food
bank and that I don't know
about or that I can't reach,

38:04.266 --> 38:07.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's those people that keep me
awake at night, those children
that I know that are out of

38:07.333 --> 38:11.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
school that aren't getting
a breakfast and lunch.

38:11.433 --> 38:16.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Some hungry families
may not be able to get to
her, but Ms. Cayce spends the

38:17.533 --> 38:19.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
rest of her day making
home deliveries.

38:19.433 --> 38:24.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Cat Wise in Thornton, Arkansas.

38:28.666 --> 38:33.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now:
Electric cars, are they
the ride of the future?

38:37.866 --> 38:42.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their potential to revolutionize
the road is once again
grabbing headlines, as some

38:42.300 --> 38:45.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
companies ramp up
production plans.

38:45.066 --> 38:49.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
William Brangham breaks down
the realities of the technology
and the market for electric

38:49.400 --> 38:51.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
vehicles.

38:51.500 --> 38:55.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He recorded this earlier for our
weekly segment on the Leading
Edge of science and technology.

38:55.333 --> 38:59.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The knock on
electric cars has always been
that they're a pricey, niche

38:59.833 --> 39:03.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
product that only a
handful of people would
want or could afford.

39:03.800 --> 39:06.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that reputation is
starting to crumble, and fast.

39:06.333 --> 39:10.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The electric car maker Tesla,
which already has a bigger
market value than General Motors

39:10.633 --> 39:15.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and Ford, will soon
be delivering its
mid-priced Model 3 car.

39:15.566 --> 39:20.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Volvo just announced that,
in two years, all of its cars
will be hybrids or electric.

39:20.433 --> 39:25.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And some major U.S.
manufacturers have
proven electric vehicles
available right now.

39:26.866 --> 39:28.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, are electric vehicles
ready to go mainstream?

39:28.600 --> 39:30.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NPR's Sonari Glinton has
been covering the story.

39:30.666 --> 39:31.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And he joins me now.

39:31.666 --> 39:32.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome to the "NewsHour."

39:32.900 --> 39:35.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
